## What happened

In **.NET 11**, Apple's cryptography libraries dropped DSA support, and .NET passes that through — **`DSA.Create()` now throws on macOS**. This is a behavioral (runtime) breaking change; the code still compiles fine but fails at runtime.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy DSA signatures (not create new ones), you have two practical options:

### Option 1 — Platform-guard the DSA path (keep legacy verification on Windows/Linux)

```csharp
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;

if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.OSX))
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
        "DSA signature verification is not supported on macOS in .NET 11+.");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Option 2 — Migrate signatures to a modern algorithm (recommended long-term)

Re-sign your data with **ECDsa** or **RSA** and retire the DSA code path entirely:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
ecdsa.ImportParameters(newPublicKey);
bool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, newSignature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Recommendation

DSA is a legacy algorithm everywhere — even Windows/Linux support is maintained only for backward compatibility. The safest long-term fix is **Option 2**: re-sign with ECDSA/RSA and drop the DSA dependency entirely. If you must keep verifying old signatures during a transition period, use the platform guard (Option 1) so macOS builds fail gracefully instead of with an unhandled exception.
